{"title_page": "James Cruickshank", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist   <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = James Cruickshank\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| background     =   non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = James Watson<ref>{{Citation | last = Thompson | first = Angela | author-link = | date = 24 October 2015 | title = Cruickshank surf prize honours Cruel Sea legend | periodical = Illawarra Mercury | url = https://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/3445148/cruickshank-surf-prize-honours-cruel-sea-legend/ }}</ref>\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = 1962\n| birth_place         = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = 8 October 2015\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = \n}}\n'''James Cruickshank''' (1962-8 October 2015) was an Australian musician and a former member of [[The Cruel Sea (band)|The Cruel Sea]].<ref name=\"The Sydney Morning Herald - 9 October 2015 - The Cruel Sea's guitarist James Cruickshank dies after cancer battle\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/the-cruel-seas-guitarist-james-cruickshank-dies-after-cancer-battle-20151009-gk5679.html|title=The Cruel Sea's guitarist James Cruickshank dies after cancer battle|date=9 October 2015|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nCruickshank was a member of the late 80s band Widdershins along with Barry Turnbull, Greg Appel, Juliet Ward and Peter Timmerman. They released one full-length album before breaking up in 1989. Cruickshank and Ward then formed Juliet Hammerhead and Friends. He later went on to play with [[Neil Murray (Australian musician)|Neil Murray]] and the Rainmakers. He was a member of [[The Blackeyed Susans]] in 1991, appearing on their [[Anchor Me (EP)|Anchor Me]] EP.\n\nCruickshank joined The Cruel Sea in 1989 and was with them until their breakup, then reuniting  with them to tour in 2008 and 2010. He continued playing with Cruel Sea bandmate [[Tex Perkins]]. He was a member of Tex Perkins And His Ladyboyz and appeared on Tex Perkins and the Dark Horses's selftitled album.\n\nCruickshank released three solo albums through Vitamin, in 2003, 2007 and 2011, and toured nationally to support them.\n\nCruickshank died on 8 October 2015 after a long battle with bowel cancer.<ref name=\"The Music Australia\">{{cite news|url=http://themusic.com.au/news/all/2015/10/09/the-cruel-sea-guitarist/keyboardist-james-cruickshank-passes-away|title=The Cruel Sea Guitarist/Keyboardist James Cruickshank Passes Away|date=9 October 2015|work=themusic.com.au|publisher=Street Press Australia Pty Ltd|accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''Hymn For Her'' (2003) - Vitamin<ref>{{Citation | last = Shedden | first = Iain | author-link = | date = 31 July 2004 | title = Mellow moods follow Cruel Sea change | periodical = The Australian | url =  }}</ref>\n*''Hello Human'' (2007) - Vitamin<ref>{{Citation | last = Apter | first = Jeff | author-link = | date = 20 July 2007 | title = CD Reviews | periodical = The Sydney Morning Herald | url =  }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last = Shedden | first = Iain | author-link = | date = 22 December 2007 | title = Spin doctor | periodical = The Australian | url =  }}</ref>\n*''Note To Self'' (2011) - Vitamin\n\nTex Perkins And His Ladyboyz\n*''No. 1's & No. 2's'' (2008) - Universal\n\nThe Cruel Sea\n*See [[The Cruel Sea (band)#Discography|The Cruel Sea Discography]]\n\nThe Blackeyed Susans\n*''Anchor Me'' EP (1991) - Waterfront Records\n\nWiddershins\n*''Ascension'' (1989) - Waterfront Records\n*''Good Songs 1987-1989'' (2005) - Egg Records\n*\"Now You Know / Dishwashing Liquid\" (1987) - Waterfront Records\n*\"Bottle Man's Wife\" (1988) - Waterfront Records\n*\"Return Of The King\" / \"Bugle Call\" (1989) - Waterfront Records\n*\"Now You Know\" (2006) - Egg Records\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jamescruickshank.com/ James Cruickshank]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cruickshank, James}}\n[[Category:Australian rock musicians]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist   <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = James Cruickshank\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| background     =   non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = James Watson<ref>{{Citation | last = Thompson | first = Angela | author-link = | date = 24 October 2015 | title = Cruickshank surf prize honours Cruel Sea legend | periodical = Illawarra Mercury | url = https://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/3445148/cruickshank-surf-prize-honours-cruel-sea-legend/ }}</ref>\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = 1962\n| birth_place         = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = 8 October 2015\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = \n}}\n'''James Cruickshank''' (1962-8 October 2015) was an Australian musician and a former member of [[The Cruel Sea (band)|The Cruel Sea]].<ref name=\"The Sydney Morning Herald - 9 October 2015 - The Cruel Sea's guitarist James Cruickshank dies after cancer battle\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/the-cruel-seas-guitarist-james-cruickshank-dies-after-cancer-battle-20151009-gk5679.html|title=The Cruel Sea's guitarist James Cruickshank dies after cancer battle|date=9 October 2015|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nCruickshank was a member of the late 80s band Widdershins along with Barry Turnbull, Greg Appel, Juliet Ward and Peter Timmerman. They released one full length album before breaking up in 1989. Cruickshank and Ward then formed Juliet Hammerhead and Friends. He later went on to play with [[Neil Murray (Australian musician)|Neil Murray]] and the Rainmakers. He was a member of [[The Blackeyed Susans]] in 1991, appearing on their [[Anchor Me (EP)|Anchor Me]] EP.\n\nCruickshank joined The Cruel Sea in 1989 and was with them until their breakup, then reuniting  with them to tour in 2008 and 2010. He continued playing with Cruel Sea band mate [[Tex Perkins]]. He was a member of Tex Perkins And His Ladyboyz and appeared on Tex Perkins and the Dark Horses's selftitled album.\n\nCruickshank released three solo albums through Vitamin, in 2003, 2007 and 2011, and toured nationally to support them.\n\nCruickshank died on 8 October 2015 after a long battle with bowel cancer.<ref name=\"The Music Australia\">{{cite news|url=http://themusic.com.au/news/all/2015/10/09/the-cruel-sea-guitarist/keyboardist-james-cruickshank-passes-away|title=The Cruel Sea Guitarist/Keyboardist James Cruickshank Passes Away|date=9 October 2015|work=themusic.com.au|publisher=Street Press Australia Pty Ltd|accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''Hymn For Her'' (2003) - Vitamin<ref>{{Citation | last = Shedden | first = Iain | author-link = | date = 31 July 2004 | title = Mellow moods follow Cruel Sea change | periodical = The Australian | url =  }}</ref>\n*''Hello Human'' (2007) - Vitamin<ref>{{Citation | last = Apter | first = Jeff | author-link = | date = 20 July 2007 | title = CD Reviews | periodical = The Sydney Morning Herald | url =  }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last = Shedden | first = Iain | author-link = | date = 22 December 2007 | title = Spin doctor | periodical = The Australian | url =  }}</ref>\n*''Note To Self'' (2011) - Vitamin\n\nTex Perkins And His Ladyboyz\n*''No. 1's & No. 2's'' (2008) - Universal\n\nThe Cruel Sea\n*See [[The Cruel Sea (band)#Discography|The Cruel Sea Discography]]\n\nThe Blackeyed Susans\n*''Anchor Me'' EP (1991) - Waterfront Records\n\nWiddershins\n*''Ascension'' (1989) - Waterfront Records\n*''Good Songs 1987-1989'' (2005) - Egg Records\n\n*\"Now You Know / Dishwashing Liquid\" (1987) - Waterfront Records\n*\"Bottle Man's Wife\" (1988) - Waterfront Records\n*\"Return Of The King\" / \"Bugle Call\" (1989) - Waterfront Records\n*\"Now You Know\" (2006) - Egg Records\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jamescruickshank.com/ James Cruickshank]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cruickshank, James}}\n[[Category:Australian rock musicians]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: band mate \u2192 bandmate, full length \u2192 full-length", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Cruickshank"}
{"title_page": "Vigo\u2013Peinador Airport", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Vigo Airport\n| nativename   = <small>''Aeropuerto de Vigo''</small>\n| nativename-a =\n| nativename-r = <small>''Aeroporto de Vigo''</small>\n| image        = Aena_Vigo.svg\n| image-width  = 250\n| image2        = Aeropuerto_de_Vigo,_foto_aerea.jpg\n| image2-width  = 250\n| IATA         = VGO\n| ICAO         = LEVX\n| FAA          =\n| LID          =\n| pushpin_map  = Spain Galicia\n| pushpin_label= VGO\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport in Galicia\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = [[ENAIRE]]\n| operator     = Aena\n| city-served  = [[Vigo]], [[Spain]]\n| location     = [[Vigo]], [[Spain]]\n| metric-elev  =Y\n| elevation-f  = 855\n| elevation-m  = 261\n| coordinates  = {{coord|42|13|45|N|008|37|39|W|type:airport_region:ES}}\n| website      =\n| metric-rwy   = Y\n| r1-number    = 01/19\n| r1-length-f  = 7,874\n| r1-length-m  = 2,400\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| stat-year    = 2018\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data   = 1,129,689\n| stat2-header = Passengers change 17-18\n| stat2-data   = {{increase}}6.0%\n| stat3-header = Movements\n| stat3-data   = 12,526\n| stat4-header = Cargo (t)\n| stat4-data   = 1,061\n| footnotes    = Source: Spanish [[Aeronautical Information Publication|AIP]] at [[European Organisation for the Safety of Air Navigation|EUROCONTROL]], [[Aena]]<ref name=\"AIP\">[http://www.ead.eurocontrol.int/publicuser/protect/pu/main.jsp EAD Basic][http://www.aena.es/en/vigo-airport/introduction.html][http://www.aena.es/csee/ccurl/585/1010/Vigo%20Airport%202015.pdf]</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Vigo Airport''' {{airport codes|VGO|LEVX}} is {{convert|10|km|abbr=on}} east<ref name=\"AIP\"/> from the centre of [[Vigo]] and 28&nbsp;km from the centre of [[Pontevedra]] (the capital of this province), and is situated in the municipalities of [[Redondela]], [[Vigo]] and [[Mos (Spain)|Mos]], in the [[Province of Pontevedra]], [[Spain]].\n\n== History ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=February 2016}}\nBy 1927 the Spanish Government became aware of the necessity of having a customs airport in Galicia. Initially, the harbour of Vigo was equipped for seaplanes and a \"maritime airport\" was built and started operations at nearby Cesantes beach in March 1929; meanwhile the construction of a larger inland airport at Peinador was initiated.\n\nAfter years of bureaucratic struggle and negotiations from the local government, the then called Ministerio del Aire fully took on the project and restarted construction in 1947. Following completion of the airport by 1952, operations started in earnest on 20 April 1954 with a 1,500-meter runway. The initial route to Madrid was operated by Iberia flying a [[Douglas DC-3]] aircraft but after a few months Iberia handed the route to [[Aviaco]].\n\nDuring the 1970s, as traffic at the airport grew, a further development plan was initiated. This involved the construction of a new control tower in 1973, a new passenger terminal in 1974, an independent power plant in 1975 and an expansion of the apron and widening of the taxiways completed in 1976. A few years after, the runway was lengthened so [[DC-9]] series aircraft were able to use the airport. As a result, in November 1981 the airport had its first international flight to [[Paris\u2013Charles de Gaulle Airport]].\n\nIn preparation for future air traffic demands, Aena published an airport development project.\n\nIn late May 2007, the Board of Aena awarded the construction of the \"Vehicle Parking Building, Construction and Technical Block of Vigo airport\" to [[Dragados]] SA for an amount of 38,266,145 euros and an execution period of 28 months.\n\nAfter meeting in the summer of 2008, it was decided to expand Vigo Airport's terminal. However, it took more than a year of delays and conflicting information before a plan was finalised and, on 24 February 2010, the Board of Directors approved the expansion. The expansion is planned to add 11,200 square meters to the current terminal of 8,200 square meters and also involves the total refurbishment of the existing terminal building. The renovation and extension will raise the annual capacity of the airport to four million users.\n\nIn 2018, 1.129.689 passengers and 1.060 tonnes of goods passed through the airport.<ref>http://www.aena.es/es/corporativa/aeropuerto-vigo-vuelve-superar-millon-pasajeros-anuales-en---2018.html?p=1237548067436</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n{{Airport-dest-list\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Europa]] | [[Adolfo Su\u00e1rez Madrid\u2013Barajas Airport|Madrid]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Binter Canarias]] | [[Gran Canaria Airport|Gran Canaria]], [[Tenerife North Airport|Tenerife\u2013North]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]] | [[Adolfo Su\u00e1rez Madrid\u2013Barajas Airport|Madrid]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Iberia Express]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Tenerife North Airport|Tenerife\u2013North]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Iberia Regional]] | [[Bilbao Airport|Bilbao]], [[Adolfo Su\u00e1rez Madrid\u2013Barajas Airport|Madrid]], [[Valencia Airport|Valencia]] <br> '''Seasonal:''' Alicante ,  [[Charles de Gaulle Airport|Paris\u2013Charles de Gaulle]] (ends 30 October 2020)\n<!-- -->\n|[[Vueling]] | [[Barcelona\u2013El Prat Airport|Barcelona]]\n<!-- -->\n}}\n\n==Ground transportation==\n[[File:Aeroportodevigo.jpg|thumb|Inside the terminal]]\n[[File:Vigo airport transit map.jpg|thumb|Vigo airport transit map]]\nVigo Airport is connected to [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] and [[North Portugal]] by different transportation networks. The city public company of transport is Vitrasa, and it\u00b4s 9A line works near the arrival\u00b4s hall at the terminal. The single fare is 1,35\u20ac.\n\n===Train===\n[[Vigo-Urz\u00e1iz railway station]] is connected to the airport directly by bus line 9A every 30 minutes at Urzaiz (Muro estaci\u00f3n) switch (journey time from the airport to [[Vigo-Urzaiz railway station]]: 25 minutes). It provides high speed connectivity to [[Pontevedra]], [[Vilagarc\u00eda de Arousa]], [[Santiago de Compostela]] and [[A Coru\u00f1a]]. [[Vigo-Guixar railway station]] is connected to the airport by bus lines 8, 16 and 24 in connection with bus line 9A at Urz\u00e1iz 13 switch. It provides connectivity to [[Porto]], [[Pontevedra]], [[Vilagarc\u00eda de Arousa]], [[Santiago de Compostela]], [[A Coru\u00f1a]], [[Madrid]], [[Ourense]], [[Monforte de Lemos]], [[Palencia]], [[Le\u00f3n, Spain|Le\u00f3n]], [[Ponferrada]], [[Zamora, Spain|Zamora]], [[Redondela]], {{ill|Arcade, Spain|lt=Arcade|es|Arcade (Sotomayor)}},  [[Padr\u00f3n]] and [[Ordes]]. Optionally, direct line 9A from maritime station is close enough, getting off at Garc\u00eda Barb\u00f3n, 16 switch (15 minutes walking approximately).\n\n===Bus===\nVigo bus station is connected to the airport by [[Vitrasa]] bus lines 4C and 23 in connection with line 9A at Travesia de Vigo 7 switch (journey time from the airport to Travesia de Vigo, 7 switch: 22 minutes). It provides connectivity to the rest of [[Vigo metropolitan area|metropolitan area]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], [[Portugal]] and several [[Spain|Spanish]] cities as [[Salamanca]], [[Oviedo]], [[Madrid]], [[Bilbao]], [[Pamplona]], [[Zaragoza]] or [[Barcelona]]. Urban transit service [[Vitrasa]] connects the airport with the city center with the line 9A every 30 minutes.\n\n===Car===\nA close access exists from [[Autopista AP-9|AP-9]] motorway near Puxeiros road junction, connecting to the downtown, the rest of Galicia and Portugal. Travel time to the [[Vigo|city]] center is around 20 minutes.\n\n== Catchment area ==\n[[File:VGO.png|thumb|Vigo airport catchment area]]\n[[Vigo]] airport is located in the center of the [[Galicia\u2013North Portugal Euroregion]]. This situation together with the fact of being a well communicated [[airport]] provides it the largest [[catchment area]] of [[Galicia (Spain)|Galician]] airports for all [[isochronous]], being the second one in the [[Galicia\u2013North Portugal Euroregion|euroregion]] after [[Porto]] airport.\n<ref>http://www.ine.es/dynt3/inebase/index.htm?padre=517</ref><ref>http://censos.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xpid=CENSOS&xpgid=ine_censos_publicacoes</ref><ref>https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/distancematrix/json</ref> Besides the city of [[Vigo]], the airport catchment area includes some touristic destinations like [[R\u00edas Baixas]], [[North Portugal]] and [[Santiago de Compostela]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! 30 min\n! 60 min\n! 90 min\n! 120 min\n|-\n| 528,938\n| 1,100,385\n| 3,885,134\n| 5,738,220\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n* [http://www.aena.es/en/vigo-airport/index.html Official website]\n* [http://www.vitrasa.es/FotosFichas/lineas14/HP_WEB_L9A_V04.pdf Timetable of L9A bus line]\n\n{{Portalbar|Spain|Aviation}}\n{{Airports in Spain}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vigo-Peinador Airport}}\n[[Category:Airports in Galicia (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Province of Pontevedra]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1952]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Vigo Airport\n| nativename   = <small>''Aeropuerto de Vigo''</small>\n| nativename-a =\n| nativename-r = <small>''Aeroporto de Vigo''</small>\n| image        = Aena_Vigo.svg\n| image-width  = 200\n| image2        = Aeropuerto_de_Vigo,_foto_aerea.jpg\n| image2-width  = 250\n| IATA         = VGO\n| ICAO         = LEVX\n| FAA          =\n| LID          =\n| pushpin_map  = Spain Galicia\n| pushpin_label= VGO\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport in Galicia\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = [[ENAIRE]]\n| operator     = Aena\n| city-served  = [[Vigo]], [[Spain]]\n| location     = [[Vigo]], [[Spain]]\n| metric-elev  =Y\n| elevation-f  = 855\n| elevation-m  = 261\n| coordinates  = {{coord|42|13|45|N|008|37|39|W|type:airport_region:ES}}\n| website      =\n| metric-rwy   = Y\n| r1-number    = 01/19\n| r1-len